10. ENFORCEMENT
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

   Unauthorised Use, unauthorised forking, unauthorised cloning,
   unauthorised creation of Derivatives, or failure to maintain
   Attribution constitutes:

   (a) infringement of copyright under Section 51 of the Copyright
       Act, 1957, entitling the Owner to civil remedies under
       Section 55 of the said Act, including injunction, damages,
       and accounts of profits;

   (b) a cognisable and non-bailable offence under Section 63 of the
       Copyright Act, 1957, punishable with imprisonment for a term
       not less than six (6) months and which may extend to three (3)
       years, and with fine which shall not be less than fifty
       thousand rupees and which may extend to two lakh rupees, with
       enhanced penalties on second or subsequent conviction under
       Section 63A;

   (c) where the infringement involves the knowing use of an
       infringing copy of a computer programme, an offence under
       Section 63B of the Copyright Act, 1957;

   (d) where applicable, an offence under Sections 65A (circumvention
       of effective technological protection measures) and 65B
       (removal or alteration of rights management information) of
       the Copyright Act, 1957;

   (e) where applicable, an offence under Section 65 (tampering with
       computer source documents), Section 66 (computer-related
       offences), and Section 66B (dishonestly receiving stolen
       computer resource or communication device) of the Information
       Technology Act, 2000, and an actionable wrong under Section 43
       of the said Act; and

   (f) where applicable, offences under the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita,
       2023, including those relating to cheating and criminal breach
       of trust.

   The Owner reserves all rights and remedies available under Indian
   law, including without limitation: permanent and interim injunctive
   relief under Sections 36 to 42 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963,
   and Order XXXIX of the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908; ex parte
   Anton Piller and John Doe orders where appropriate; actual and
   statutory damages; account of profits; delivery-up and destruction
   of infringing copies under Section 58 of the Copyright Act, 1957;
   recovery of legal costs on a full indemnity basis; and criminal
   prosecution. Pursuit of one remedy shall not preclude the
   simultaneous or subsequent pursuit of any other.

   Nothing in this Section shall limit the Owner's right to enforce
   this licence under the laws of any other jurisdiction in which an
   infringement occurs or has effect.

